Ticket ID: SEC-DEV-2026-03-09-01
Title: Personal Device Security Hardening and Preventive Malware Risk Assessment
Classification: Endpoint Security Architecture / Preventive Security Hardening
Execution Date: 9 March 2026
Status: Resolved

Executive Summary
This activity documents a preventive security hardening process conducted on a personal computing environment used for professional activities, account management, and long-term digital asset protection.
The objective of the activity was not to respond to a confirmed compromise but to reduce the system’s attack surface and validate the integrity of the environment.
The review included a structured analysis of potential compromise scenarios, including credential theft risks, malware persistence mechanisms, removable media infection vectors, and system-level security configuration.
As part of the process, system verification procedures were performed, security configurations were reviewed, and layered defensive controls were implemented.
The result is a hardened personal computing environment designed to minimize exposure to common attack vectors while maintaining practical usability.

Project Objective
The primary objective of this activity was to ensure that the user’s computing environment maintains a strong preventive security posture against potential external threats.
These threats could include:
	• unauthorized credential access through external data breaches
	• malware introduced through compromised third-party sources
	• persistent system-level threats
	• removable media infection vectors
	• potential credential harvesting attempts
The activity was conducted as a preventive risk reduction exercise, ensuring that the system environment adheres to modern personal cybersecurity practices.

System Environment
The computing environment consists of the following devices and operating systems.
Primary Workstation
Operating systems:
	• Windows 11 Home (fully updated)
	• Linux distribution (dual-boot configuration)
The dual operating system architecture provides flexibility for system management, experimentation, and environment separation.

Authentication Device
Authentication codes are generated on a dedicated mobile device.
Device characteristics:
	• iPhone
	• non-jailbroken operating system
	• only trusted applications installed
	• used for two-factor authentication
This separation ensures that authentication factors remain independent from the primary workstation.

Preventive Security Measures Implemented
Several security measures were implemented or validated during this activity.

Operating System Integrity Verification
The Windows environment underwent verification and cleanup procedures to ensure system integrity.
Actions performed included:
	• confirming operating system updates
	• reviewing security configuration
	• performing system cleanup and verification procedures
	• validating Windows Defender status
	• confirming absence of suspicious software
A TRON script execution was also performed as an additional verification and cleanup step.

Security Hardening
Additional configuration adjustments were applied to ensure a hardened system baseline.
These included:
	• maintaining active security monitoring
	• minimizing unnecessary background software
	• ensuring system services are operating within normal parameters
	• maintaining a clean and stable operating environment
The system is now operating with a minimal software footprint, reducing potential attack surface.

Removable Media Risk Mitigation
As part of the preventive investigation, removable storage devices were reviewed.
USB drives were subjected to a complete reset process to ensure that no legacy data structures remained.
Actions performed included:
	• deletion of all partitions
	• recreation of new partitions
	• full formatting procedures
These steps ensure that any standard removable media malware or hidden file-based threats are eliminated.

Firmware-Level Threat Evaluation
The investigation also reviewed extremely advanced attack scenarios involving firmware-level persistence.
Examples of such threats include:
	• USB controller firmware modification
	• motherboard firmware compromise
	• boot firmware manipulation
These attack vectors are generally associated with highly specialized targeted operations requiring direct physical access and specialized tools.
No indicators suggested such activity.
Because these scenarios require direct physical interaction with hardware, they were assessed as extremely unlikely within the user's operational environment.

Remote Malware Risk Evaluation
The possibility of remote malware installation was also considered as part of the review.
Modern operating systems include significant protections against unauthorized remote installation of malicious software.
Because the system environment is maintained with:
	• current operating system updates
	• active security monitoring
	• trusted software sources only
the likelihood of remote compromise was assessed as low.

Encryption Considerations
Full disk encryption using BitLocker was evaluated during the security review.
However, the system operates in a dual-boot configuration with Linux, which introduces compatibility limitations with standard BitLocker deployment.
Given the following considerations:
	• the device operates in a controlled environment
	• physical device exposure risk is low
	• sensitive account credentials are stored in a secure password manager rather than local files
full disk encryption was not implemented at this stage.
The option remains available if the system architecture changes in the future.

Security Hardware Token Evaluation
Hardware authentication tokens were also evaluated.
However, the user maintains authentication across a large number of services, and platform support for hardware tokens remains inconsistent across many providers.
Because the environment already uses:
	• strong password management
	• device-based two-factor authentication
hardware tokens were considered optional rather than necessary for the current setup.

Risk Assessment Summary
After completing the hardening process, the system environment demonstrates strong resilience against common attack vectors.
Threat Category	Risk Level	Notes
Credential compromise from external breaches	Low	mitigated by password manager and unique credentials
Malware infection	Low	hardened system environment
Removable media threats	Very Low	drives fully reset
Remote compromise	Low	updated OS and security monitoring
Firmware-level threats	Extremely Low	require physical access

Outcome
This preventive security hardening process successfully validated the integrity of the user's computing environment and reduced the system’s exposure to potential external threats.
The activity resulted in:
	• verified system integrity
	• hardened operating system configuration
	• removal of legacy removable media risks
	• evaluation of advanced persistence scenarios
	• improved understanding of the system’s threat landscape
The resulting environment provides a strong baseline for maintaining long-term personal cybersecurity.
